<paragraph pageNumber="12">
FIGURE 4. Photo of a male 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Rachovia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maculipinnis">Rachovia maculipinnis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="13" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A12D02B2-18D2-450F-B6ED-A28984BAD110" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Austrofundulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Austrofundulus Myers 1932:159" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Austrofundulus</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:79CEE90A-5FE1-406E-BE38-5DF8C249CD32" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Terranatos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Terranatos Taphorn &amp; Thomerson 1978:384" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Terranatos</taxonomicName>
(see Fig. 5) in having: shorter fins, the dorsal fin less than 55% SL (range 23-47%) in males, and less than 40% SL (range 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="13">22</pageStartToken>
-40%) in females, versus more than 55% (55-124%) and more than 37% (37-47%) in males and females of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:79CEE90A-5FE1-406E-BE38-5DF8C249CD32" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Terranatos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Terranatos Taphorn &amp; Thomerson 1978:384" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Terranatos</taxonomicName>
, respectively; caudal fin scaled for more than one third of its length vs. unscaled except at base; female without extensions of caudal fin rays vs. filamentous rays on the dorsal and ventral margins; maximum standard length more than 30 mm vs. less than 30 mm SL; anal actinosts articulated with hemal spines rather than ribs.
</paragraph>
